    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Daily Practice Routine</h2>

<div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
    <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-2">📝 5 min: Word Drills</p>
    <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Flash through 20 two-letter words or anagram 5 seven-letter racks. Use spaced repetition — focus on words you keep forgetting.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
    <p class="text-blue-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-2">🎮 5 min: Anagram Practice</p>
    <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Use online anagram solvers or apps. Give yourself 30 seconds per rack. Speed builds pattern recognition that transfers to real games.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
    <p class="text-amber-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-2">♟️ 5 min: Board Study</p>
    <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Review one completed game. Find moves you missed, spots you overlooked, and better plays you could have made. Post-game analysis is the #1 accelerator.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20">
    <p class="text-purple-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-2">🎯 Play One Game</p>
    <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Play against a computer or online opponent at your level. Focus on applying one new skill per game rather than trying everything at once.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Common Mistakes That Slow Progress</h2>

<div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-500/30 bg-red-950/10">
    <p class="text-red-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✗ Playing only for highest immediate score</p>
    <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Beginners take the biggest word every turn. Better players consider rack leave — what tiles you keep matters more than what you play.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-500/30 bg-red-950/10">
    <p class="text-red-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✗ Ignoring board position</p>
    <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Opening triple-word squares for your opponent or closing the board too early costs more points than a slightly higher single-turn score.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-500/30 bg-red-950/10">
    <p class="text-red-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✗ Studying rare long words first</p>
    <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Knowing obscure 9-letter words is useless if you can't find parallel plays with 2-letter words. Build from the foundation up.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Tracking Your Progress</h2>

<div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
  <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">💡 Measure Improvement</p>
  <p class="text-base text-gray-200">Track your average score over 10 games. After 2 weeks of studying two-letter words, you should see a <span class="text-white font-medium">30-50 point increase</span> in your average. After learning bingo stems for a month, expect another <span class="text-white font-medium">40-60 point jump</span>. Measurable progress keeps motivation high.</p>
</div>

<p>Keep a simple spreadsheet or notebook logging: date, opponent strength, your score, opponent's score, number of bingos played, and notable words you missed. After 20 games, patterns emerge — showing you exactly where to focus next.</p>

